Here are some sample "Hello, World!" applications in various programming languages, including Delphi and C#:

## C# Hello World
```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

## Delphi Hello World
```pascal
program HelloWorld;

uses
  System.SysUtils;

begin
  Writeln('Hello, World!');
  Readln;
end.
```

## Python Hello World
```python
print("Hello, World!")
```

## JavaScript Hello World
```javascript
console.log("Hello, World!");
// Or for web browsers:
alert("Hello, World!");
```

## Java Hello World
```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

## C++ Hello World
```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::cout << "Hello, World!" << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

## Go Hello World
```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    fmt.Println("Hello, World!")
}
```

## Rust Hello World
```rust
fn main() {
    println!("Hello, World!");
}
```

## Ruby Hello World
```ruby
puts "Hello, World!"
```

## Swift Hello World
```swift
print("Hello, World!")
```

Each of these examples demonstrates the basic syntax for outputting text in their respective languages. The Delphi version uses Pascal syntax with `Writeln` and `Readln` for console input/output, while C# uses `Console.WriteLine` for the same purpose.
